Introduction¶

In this project i will be analyzing the data on TMDb movies. The TMDb dataset contains information about 10,000 movies collected from The Movie Database(TMDB), inluding user ratings and revenue.

Some questions to be answered from this analysis include:¶

  1. How has the growth of the film industry been over the years
  2. Which genres are most popular from year to year
  3. How is the performance of the movie industry per year in terms of revenue and budget
  4. What are the top 10 budgeted movies?

# Having asssessed the number of 0s we have in the budget and revenue column, it is quite unreasonable and unexplanable because
# every movie released must have a budget and revenue regardless of how small or big. So, i will be changing this columns with
# 0s and filling them up with the average of each.

df['budget_adj'].replace(0,df['budget_adj'].mean(), inplace=True)

Research Question 1c: How is the performance of the movie industry per year in terms of revenue and budget?¶

In [36]:
# Grouping by release_year and adding the budget for each release_year
# Grouping by release_year and adding the revenue for each release_year
# visualize the data
budget = df.groupby(['release_year']).budget_adj.sum()
revenue = df.groupby(['release_year']).revenue_adj.sum()
fig = plt.figure(figsize=(15,8))
plt.plot(budget, linewidth=3)
plt.plot(revenue, linewidth=3)
plt.title("The movie industry's total revenue and budget", fontsize = 20)
plt.xlabel("Year", fontsize=15)
plt.ylabel("Investments", fontsize=15)
plt.legend(['budget','revenue'])
plt.show()

As can be seen on the line plot above, the movie industry's total budget and revenue has been massively growing throughout the years especially after the 1990s but there has been a problem in the rate of investment(ROI). It can be observed that there has been decrement in ROI in recent years. This is clearly visualized below.¶

In [37]:
# Now to get the Return on Investment of the movie industry over the years
# visualizing the data
roi = (revenue - budget)/budget
fig = plt.figure(figsize=(15,8))
plt.bar(roi.index,roi)
plt.title('Return on investment per year', fontsize=20)
plt.xlabel('Year', fontsize=18)
plt.ylabel('Return on Investment', fontsize=18)
plt.show()

As seen above, the return on investment was at its highest between 1970 and 1980 and massively decreased in the late 90s. it has been growing as of late i.e after 2010 although the growth is nothing compared to that which happened in the 70s.¶

Research Question 1d: Has the popularity affected the revenue and budget in anyway?¶

In [38]:
# let's create a fuction that will take the data  we will need for the visualization as well as for its basic editing and output
# the required scatter plot needed for this representation. It is created so it can be re-used for the budget plot

def plot(x,y,title,xlabel,ylabel):
    fig = plt.figure(figsize=(10,6))
    plt.scatter(x,y)
    plt.title(title, fontsize=20)
    plt.xlabel(xlabel, fontsize=15)
    plt.ylabel(ylabel, fontsize=15)
    plt.xlim(0,10)
    return plt.show()

plot(df['popularity'],df['revenue_adj'],'Correlation between popularity and revenue','Popularity','Revenue in USD')

As shown above, there is no observable correlation between popularity and revenue. That is, popularity in no way affects the amount of revenue.¶

In [39]:
# Re-using the function already created above

plot(df['popularity'],df['budget_adj'],'Correlation between popularity and budget','Popularity','Budget in USD')

As shown above, there is no observable correlation between popularity and revenue. That is, popularity in no way affects the amount of revenue.¶

Research Question 1e: Which month is associated with the highest revenue and budget¶

In [41]:
# Let's now get the Return on investent per month
roi_m= (revenue_month-budget_month)/(budget_month)
fig = plt.figure(figsize=(15,6)) 
plt.bar(roi_m.index,roi_m,alpha = 0.7)
plt.title('Return on Investment Rate per Month',fontsize=18)
plt.xlabel('Month',fontsize=18)
plt.xticks(range(0,13))
plt.ylabel('ROI',fontsize=18)
plt.show()

As seen on the graph, the ROI for june and December seem to be equal. So, it can be said that the most profit is generated in the month of June and December.¶

Conclusions¶

TDMB dataset provided me with a whole lot of interesting insights about the movie industry. This insights gotten through Exploratory Data Analysis where utilized in providing answers to my numerous questions. From the research questions, the concluding insights were:

  • The movie industry is a fast growing business over the past 50 years. There has been a massive growth since after 90s and the release of movies skyrocketed since after 2005.
  • The genre with the highest revenue per year is "WAR" in the year "2009" with a revenue of over 2.8 billion USD and then closely followed by "Western" in the year "1977" with a revenue of almost 2.8 billion USD.
  • The movie industry's total budget and revenue has been massively growing throughout the years especially after the 90s but there has been a problem in the rate of investment(ROI) as the return on investment was at its highest between 1970 and 1980 and massively decreased in the late 90s. it has been growing as of late i.e after 2010, although the growth is nothing compared to that which happened in the 70s.
  • There is no observable correlation between (popularity and revenue) or (popularity and budget). That is, popularity in no way affects the amount of revenue or the amount of budget.
  • The movie with the highest budget is "The Warrior's Way" with a budget of around 425 million USD followed by "Pirates of the Carribean: On the Stranger Tides" with a budget of 368 million USD. This two movies are considered to be the most expensive movies.
  • The production company with the highest revenue of around 3.7 billion USD for a year is "Walt Disney Pictures" and this was generated in the year "2010".
  • The genres "Action","Drama" and "Comedy" are the top 3 most budgeted genre in the movie industry i.e They are the most expensive genre.
  • Being the most popular director doesn't necessarily mean you would have the highest revenue. So the popularity of the directors has no influence on the revenue generated by each director. The most popular director "Christopher Nolan" made a total revenue of around 4 billion USD while the second most popular director "Steven Spielberg" made around 15 billion USD which proves the statement made earlier.
  • The movie "Avatar" produced the highest revenue with an amount of around 2.8 million USD and was closely followed by the movie "Star Wars" with a revenue of around 2.7 million USD. These movies are considered to be the movies with the highest gross.
  • The genre "Drama" is the genre with highest movie released which is 2223 and followed closely by Comedy with 2084 movies released and so on. "Drama" is not only the biggest genre in the movie industry it also has the fastest growing rate over the years.
  • The most successful production company based on ROI is Dry County Films followed closely by Paramount Pictures.

Limitations:

  • Of the 10866 movies present in the dataset, around 10% contained missing values which were consequently dropped and this could affect the quality and accuracy of the analysis.
  • Some of the variables like “Popularity, vote_count, vote_average” and many others were not defined in the original document from Kaggle which limits the ability to use it in the analysis.
  • Due to the numerous zero records in the revenue and budget column, i replaced this 0 value with their respective means which could have also tampered with the quality and accuracy of my results.
